{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c46d7237-ac34-4ec2-a3aa-c54b0bd241f2","content":"Use `#if` platform conditionals inside `CreateMauiApp()` to register the right implementation per target:\n\n```csharp\n// MauiProgram.cs\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- The symbols `ANDROID`, `IOS`, `WINDOWS` are defined automatically by the MAUI SDK for each target framework.\n- Each platform-specific class lives under `Platforms/<platform>/` and implements the shared `INotificationService` interface.\n- Only the implementation for the current build target gets compiled in, so there's no risk of referencing unavailable platform APIs.\n- Inject `INotificationService` into your pages/viewmodels via constructor injection as usual.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"38e3c06b-ab68-467c-8d38-0751224c71a7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection setup for platform-specific services. This is a general knowledge question about MAUI development patterns — no codebase exploration needed.","outputTokens":360,"requestId":"9816:155537:1714169:19B2AFE:6A052094"},"id":"277a9a8a-14fb-46d2-8ae7-9572296d28a1","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:08:44.836Z","parentId":"f734144f-b146-4414-b157-ff7929f9a992"}
